summary: Hello Thea! Is there a particular name for the branch of biology focused on Pokemon? If there isn't, what do you think a good...
question: Hello Thea! Is there a particular name for the branch of biology focused on Pokemon? If there isn't, what do you think a good name would be?
answer:
Very good question! Most of the time, researchers say just ‘pokebiology’ if they want to specify that they are studying the lives of Pokémon and not humans or plants. Prodiology is also used sometimes, and so is zoology, referring to the study of Pokémon as battling creatures and the study of Pokémon as functional living bodies, respectively.

-Thea

summary: Inktober Day 5- Chicken Mega Poxadoodle- Foul Fowl Pokémon Type- Dark/Poison Ability- Pathogenic Mega evolves from Poxadoodle...
caption:
Inktober Day 5- Chicken

Mega Poxadoodle- Foul Fowl Pokémon

Type- Dark/Poison

Ability- Pathogenic

Mega evolves from Poxadoodle when holding the Poxadite.

The power of Mega Evolution causes Mega Poxadoodle’s feather mass to increase in density greatly and encourages the infectious bacteria that live on it to grow wildly. Its tail drips with a greasy oil that spreads its germs everywhere. Legend says that merely looking at Mega Poxadoodle can infect you with terrible rashes, but this is a misconception; it’s just that if you’re close enough to one to see it, you’ll probably end up inhaling some of its bacteria. Its call is hoarse and ear-splitting.

Pathogenic is a new ability in Novrai. When an opponent makes contact with a Pokémon with Pathogenic, its ability is overwritten with Pathogenic. Additionally, any non-Poison-type Pokémon with Pathogenic lose 1/16th of their health at the end of each turn.

I still don’t actually plan on including Mega Evolutions in Novrai, but I didn’t want to design an entirely separate chicken-based line when I had this one, and I also didn’t want to just redraw Itcheep and Poxadoodle, so here you go.

Caught my mascot pokemon finally!!^^ Shes not named yet but ill think of 1 soon. funny story behind her~

I decided to shiny chain today (since i got my charm~) while i sat in front of b&n for the nycc exclusive funko pops, and plugged the charger n2 my ds overnite.

it wasnt plugged n2 the wall.

this is after 2 weekends ago i spent 4.5hrs and encountered 236mimikyus w/o the charm. i was so happy!!^^

next im goin4eevee^^

blog.name: pokebiologist

blog.description: I'm Theodora, but you can call me Thea! I'm a Battle Girl turned Pokémon Researcher, and I'm excited to share my observations with you. Feel free to ask, submit, request, and share your own findings!

summary: I was looking into getting a Torterra. Any care advice?
question: I was looking into getting a Torterra. Any care advice?
answer:
Pruning the plant growth on their backs is an absolute must! Dead or overgrown areas can cause discomfort and infection, which of course you don’t want. In the wild, Torterra often form symbiotic relationships with small arboreal Pokémon that would eat excess fruits leaves and twigs.

Additionally, make sure your pal has enough water! They go through a lot, and if you can I’d recommend providing mineral-rich water in order to keep your Torterra performing best in battle or competition.

-Thea
